---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "") + "/";
---

<DocsLayout title="Quick Start">
  <h1>Quick Start</h1>
  <p>
    Get a working Workspaces instance and run a real authorization decision in
    about five minutes. You will bring up the service with Docker Compose, list
    a user's workspaces, create a team, add a member, run <code>Check</code>,
    and share a resource with a single tuple — all against the Connect JSON API.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Start the stack</h2>
  <p>
    The repo ships a <code>docker-compose.yml</code> that brings up Postgres and
    the workspaces service together. Set
    <code>GATEWAY_SERVICE_AUTH_TOKENS</code> to one or more service credentials
    your product backend will present; here we use a single token.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`# In docker-compose.yml, the workspaces service sets:
#   GATEWAY_SERVICE_AUTH_TOKENS=dev-service-token
#   GATEWAY_DEFAULT_PROJECT_ID=default
docker compose up -d

# health probes
curl http://localhost:8080/healthz
curl http://localhost:8080/readyz`}
    lang="bash"
    title="docker compose"
  />
  <p>
    Pending migrations apply automatically on first connect while
    <code>GATEWAY_POSTGRES_AUTO_MIGRATE=true</code> (the default). Export the
    service token so the curls below can reuse it:
  </p>
  <Code code={`export WS_SERVICE_TOKEN=dev-service-token`} lang="bash" />
  <aside class="not-prose my-6 rounded-md border-l-4 border-primary bg-muted/40 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
    The Bearer token is the <strong>service</strong> credential — it identifies
    your product backend, not the end user. The end user is passed as data, in
    the request body. A missing or wrong token returns HTTP <code>401</code> /
    Connect <code>Unauthenticated</code>.
  </aside>

  <h2>2. List alice's workspaces</h2>
  <p>
    Every RPC is a POST to <code>/workspace.v1.&lt;Service&gt;/&lt;Method&gt;</code>
    with the request message as a JSON body. Management RPCs require
    <code>acting_user_id</code> — the user the action is authorized as.
    <code>ListWorkspaces</code> auto-provisions that user's
    <code>PERSONAL</code> workspace on first call.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.WorkspaceService/ListWorkspaces \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"acting_user_id":"alice"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code
    code={`{
  "workspaces": [
    {
      "id": "ws_personal_alice",
      "projectId": "default",
      "slug": "alice",
      "displayName": "alice",
      "type": "WORKSPACE_TYPE_PERSONAL",
      "ownerUserId": "alice"
    }
  ]
}`}
    lang="json"
  />
  <aside class="not-prose my-6 rounded-md border-l-4 border-primary bg-muted/40 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
    The personal workspace is <strong>closed</strong>: a single member (the
    owner), no members can be added, and it cannot be deleted. Team workspaces
    are where collaboration happens.
  </aside>

  <h2>3. Create a team workspace</h2>
  <p>
    Create a <code>TEAM</code> workspace named "Acme". The acting user becomes
    its owner.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.WorkspaceService/CreateWorkspace \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"acting_user_id":"alice","display_name":"Acme","slug":"acme"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code
    code={`{
  "workspace": {
    "id": "acme",
    "projectId": "default",
    "slug": "acme",
    "displayName": "Acme",
    "type": "WORKSPACE_TYPE_TEAM",
    "ownerUserId": "alice"
  }
}`}
    lang="json"
  />
  <p>
    Ownership is recorded as the tuple
    <code>workspace:acme#owner@user:alice</code>, so a <code>Check</code> against
    the <code>workspace</code> namespace honours it immediately.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Add bob as a member</h2>
  <p>
    Add <code>bob</code> to Acme at <code>ROLE_MEMBER</code>.
    <code>AddMember</code> writes <code>workspace:acme#member@user:bob</code>.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.WorkspaceService/AddMember \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"acting_user_id":"alice","workspace_id":"acme","user_id":"bob","role":"ROLE_MEMBER"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <aside class="not-prose my-6 rounded-md border-l-4 border-primary bg-muted/40 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
    <code>AddMember</code> rejects <code>ROLE_OWNER</code> — ownership is set at
    creation, not granted later. Roles nest:
    owner ⊃ admin ⊃ member ⊃ guest.
  </aside>

  <h2>5. Check the decision</h2>
  <p>
    Ask whether <code>bob</code> is a member of Acme — then whether he is an
    admin. <code>Check</code> evaluates the namespace's userset-rewrite rules
    transitively and answers <code>allowed</code>.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`# workspace:acme#member@bob  -> allowed
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.AuthzService/Check \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"namespace":"workspace","object_id":"acme","relation":"member","subject_user_id":"bob"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code code={`{ "allowed": true }`} lang="json" />
  <Code
    code={`# workspace:acme#admin@bob  -> denied (member is not admin)
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.AuthzService/Check \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"namespace":"workspace","object_id":"acme","relation":"admin","subject_user_id":"bob"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code code={`{ "allowed": false }`} lang="json" />
  <p>
    <code>member</code> unions in <code>admin</code> and <code>owner</code>, so
    alice (the owner) passes a member check too — but the reverse does not hold,
    so bob's <code>admin</code> check is denied.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Share a resource with a tuple</h2>
  <p>
    The engine is generic, not limited to workspaces. Grant <code>bob</code>
    direct <code>viewer</code> access to a product object <code>doc1</code> in
    the <code>resource</code> namespace, then check it.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.AuthzService/WriteRelationTuples \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{
    "updates": [
      {
        "op": "OPERATION_INSERT",
        "tuple": {
          "namespace": "resource",
          "object_id": "doc1",
          "relation": "viewer",
          "subject": { "user_id": "bob" }
        }
      }
    ]
  }'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code
    code={`curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/workspace.v1.AuthzService/Check \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $WS_SERVICE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"namespace":"resource","object_id":"doc1","relation":"viewer","subject_user_id":"bob"}'`}
    lang="bash"
  />
  <Code code={`{ "allowed": true }`} lang="json" />
  <p>
    That single tuple — <code>resource:doc1#viewer@user:bob</code> — is the
    whole grant. No per-resource table, no schema change.
  </p>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={`${base}docs/concepts/authorization-model`}>Authorization Model</a>
      — how <code>Check</code> evaluates rewrites
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={`${base}docs/concepts/workspaces-and-groups`}>Workspaces &amp; Groups</a>
      — the product surface over the engine
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={`${base}api`}>Live API Reference</a> — every RPC and message
    </li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
